# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: synthetic-monitoring
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] Navigation Timing is part of the Performance API and provides metrics associated with navigating from one page to another.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] For example, you can determine how much time it takes to load or unload a document, or log the time it took until DOM construction has finished and interaction with the DOM is possible.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] Only the current document is included, so usually there is only one `PerformanceNavigationTiming` object to observe.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] It extends the `PerformanceEntry` interface with the `entryType` of `"navigation"` and also inherits from `PerformanceResourceTiming`, so all of the timestamps from the process of fetching the document are available as well.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] (Timestamp diagram listing timestamps in the order in which they are recorded for the fetching of a document) Figure 1.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] `unloadEventStart`: (if there is a previous document) the timestamp immediately before the current document's `unload` event handler starts.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] `unloadEventEnd`: (if there is a previous document) the timestamp immediately after the current document's `unload` event handler completes.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] `domInteractive`: timestamp when DOM construction is finished and interaction with it from JavaScript is possible.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] `domContentLoadedEventStart`: timestamp immediately before the current document's `DOMContentLoaded` event handler starts.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] `domContentLoadedEventEnd`: timestamp immediately after the current document's `DOMContentLoaded` event handler completes.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] `domComplete`: timestamp when the document and all sub-resources have finished loading.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] `loadEventStart`: timestamp immediately before the current document's `load` event handler starts.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] `loadEventEnd`: timestamp immediately after the current document's `load` event handler completes.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] The `PerformanceNavigationTiming.confidence` property returns a `PerformanceTimingConfidence` object containing information that indicates whether a performance record reflects typical application performance, or is likely affected by external factors.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] For example, if a website has loaded after a browser "cold start" or session restore, its pages may load more slowly as a result.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] In such cases, a `low` confidence `value` would be returned for an associated performance record.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] On the other hand, if the browser determines a returned performance record to be representative of typical application performance, a `high` confidence value is returned.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] This confidence measure is useful for developers when trying to determine whether a performance issue is a legitimate concern, or an outlier being caused by external factors.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] See `PerformanceTimingConfidence` for more information.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] The `PerformanceNavigationTiming` interface provides additional properties such as `redirectCount` returning the number of redirects and `type` indicating the type of navigation.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] The `domContentLoadedEventEnd` and `domContentLoadedEventStart` timestamps can be used to measure how long it takes to process the `DOMContentLoaded` event handler.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] This example uses a `PerformanceObserver`, which notifies the caller about new `navigation` performance entries as they are recorded in the browser's performance timeline.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] The example uses the `buffered` option to access entries that were recorded before the observer was created.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/navigation-timing-api] For more examples, see the property pages in the `PerformanceNavigationTiming` reference documentation.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] It’s been available across browsers since October 2021.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] The **`PerformanceNavigationTiming`** interface provides methods and properties to store and retrieve metrics regarding the browser's document navigation events.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] For example, this interface can be used to determine how much time it takes to load or unload a document.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] Only the current document is included in the performance timeline, so there is only one `PerformanceNavigationTiming` object in the performance timeline.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] It inherits all of the properties and methods of `PerformanceResourceTiming` and `PerformanceEntry`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] The following diagram shows all of the timestamp properties defined in `PerformanceNavigationTiming`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] Note that text fragments, and any other fragment directives, are stripped from the URL.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] Returns a `DOMHighResTimeStamp` with a value of `0`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] Returns a `timestamp` that is the difference between the `PerformanceNavigationTiming.loadEventEnd` and `PerformanceEntry.startTime` properties.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time between when a document starts prerendering and when it is activated.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A `PerformanceTimingConfidence` object containing information that indicates whether a performance record reflects typical application performance, or is likely affected by external factors.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time at which the connection restart occurred due to `Critical-CH` HTTP response header mismatch.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately before the user agent sets the document's `readyState` to `"complete"`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately after the current document's `DOMContentLoaded` event handler completes.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately before the current document's `DOMContentLoaded` event handler starts.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately before the user agent sets the document's `readyState` to `"interactive"`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately after the current document's `load` event handler completes.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately before the current document's `load` event handler starts.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A `NotRestoredReasons` object providing report data on reasons why the current document was blocked from using the back/forward cache (bfcache) on navigation.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A number representing the number of redirects since the last non-redirect navigation in the current browsing context.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A string representing the navigation type.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately after the current document's `unload` event handler completes.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately before the current document's `unload` event handler starts.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performancenavigationtiming] Returns a JSON representation of the `PerformanceNavigationTiming` object.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] It’s been available across browsers since September 2017.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] The **`PerformanceResourceTiming`** interface enables retrieval and analysis of detailed network timing data regarding the loading of an application's resources.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] An application can use the timing metrics to determine, for example, the length of time it takes to fetch a specific resource, such as an `XMLHttpRequest`, `<SVG>`, image, or script.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] The interface's properties create a resource loading timeline with high-resolution timestamps for network events such as redirect start and end times, fetch start, DNS lookup start and end times, response start and end times, and more.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] Additionally, the interface extends `PerformanceEntry` with other properties which provide data about the size of the fetched resource as well as the type of resource that initiated the fetch.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] The properties of this interface allow you to calculate certain resource timing metrics.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] By default only 250 resource timing entries are buffered.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] For more information see the resource buffer sizes of the Resource Timing guide.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] Many of the resource timing properties are restricted to return `0` or an empty string when the resource is a cross-origin request.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] To expose cross-origin timing information, the `Timing-Allow-Origin` HTTP response header needs to be set.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] The properties which are returned as `0` by default when loading a resource from an origin other than the one of the web page itself: `redirectStart`, `redirectEnd`, `domainLookupStart`, `domainLookupEnd`, `connectStart`, `connectEnd`, `secureConnectionStart`, `requestStart`, and `responseStart`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] Returns a `timestamp` that is the difference between the `responseEnd` and the `startTime` properties.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] Returns the `timestamp` for the time a resource fetch started.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] This value is equivalent to `PerformanceResourceTiming.fetchStart`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] The interface supports the following timestamp properties which you can see in the diagram and are listed in the order in which they are recorded for the fetching of a resource.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] An alphabetical listing is shown in the navigation, at left.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` that represents the start time of the fetch which initiates the redirect.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately after receiving the last byte of the response of the last redirect.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] Returns a `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately before dispatching the `FetchEvent` if a Service Worker thread is already running, or immediately before starting the Service Worker thread if it is not already running.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] If the resource is not intercepted by a Service Worker the property will always return 0.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately before the browser starts to fetch the resource.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately before the browser starts the domain name lookup for the resource.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately after the browser finishes the domain name lookup for the resource.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately before the browser starts to establish the connection to the server to retrieve the resource.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately before the browser starts the handshake process to secure the current connection.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately after the browser finishes establishing the connection to the server to retrieve the resource.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately before the browser starts requesting the resource from the server.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` that represents the interim response time (for example, 100 Continue or 103 Early Hints).
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately after the browser receives the first byte of the response from the server (which may be an interim response).
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` that represents the final headers response time (for example, 200 Success), after any interim response time.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` immediately after the browser receives the last byte of the resource or immediately before the transport connection is closed, whichever comes first.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A string representing a minimized and standardized version of the MIME-type of the fetched resource.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A number that is the size (in octets) received from the fetch (HTTP or cache) of the message body, after removing any applied content encoding.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] Indicates how the resource was delivered — for example from the cache or from a navigational prefetch.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A number representing the size (in octets) received from the fetch (HTTP or cache), of the payload body, before removing any applied content encodings.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A string representing the web platform feature that initiated the performance entry.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A string representing the network protocol used to fetch the resource, as identified by the ALPN Protocol ID (RFC7301).
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A string representing the render-blocking status.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] Either `"blocking"` or `"non-blocking"`.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A number representing the HTTP response status code returned when fetching the resource.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] A number representing the size (in octets) of the fetched resource.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] The size includes the response header fields plus the response payload body.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] An array of `PerformanceServerTiming` entries containing server timing metrics.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] Returns a JSON representation of the `PerformanceResourceTiming` object.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] Example using a `PerformanceObserver`, which notifies of new `resource` performance entries as they are recorded in the browser's performance timeline.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/performanceresourcetiming] Use the `buffered` option to access entries from before the observer creation.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] In software design, web design, and electronic product design, **synthetic monitoring** (also known as ***active monitoring** or **proactive monitoring***) is a monitoring technique that is done by using a simulation or scripted recordings of transactions.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] Behavioral scripts (or paths) are created to simulate an action or path that a customer or end user would take on a site, application, or other software (or even hardware).
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] Those paths are then continuously monitored at specified intervals for performance, such as functionality, availability, and response time measures.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] Synthetic monitoring enables a webmaster or an IT/Operations professional to identify problems and determine if a website or application is slow or experiencing downtime before that problem affects actual end users or customers.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] This type of monitoring does not require actual traffic, thus the name synthetic, as it enables companies to test applications 24x7, or test new applications prior to a live customer-facing launch.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] Because synthetic monitoring is a simulation of typical user behavior or navigation through a website, it is often best used to monitor commonly trafficked paths and critical business processes.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] Synthetic tests must be scripted in advance, so it is not feasible to measure performance for every permutation of a navigational path an end user might take.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] These scripts are then injected into the code of the application or website, which is then tested under artificial loads.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] This, of course, can be a contrast to actual load/traffic when the design goes live.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] In this case, real user monitoring is performed, where the performance metrics are tested against real loads.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] This is more suited for passive monitoring.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] Synthetic testing is useful for measuring uptime, availability, and response time of critical pages and transactions (how a site performs from all geographies) but doesn't monitor or capture actual end user interactions, see Website monitoring.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] Synthetic monitoring will report myriad metrics, and it's up to the a webmaster or an IT/Operations professional to identify which ones are most important.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] Common metrics from synthetic website monitoring includes Time to First Byte, Speed Index, Time to Interactive, and Page Complete.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] Demand for synthetic monitoring has grown exponentially corresponding to the underlying growth in websites/applications.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] IT/Operations staff need mechanisms to identify health and performance issues in advance of their customers identifying and reporting them to avoid customer satisfaction issues.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] To accomplish this they can write custom simulation scripts, or leverage the growing number of commercial synthetic monitoring solutions.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/synthetic-monitoring] By implementing Synthetic Monitoring IT/Operations staffs are able to identify application issues in advance of them becoming critical, and take remedial action.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Faster website download speeds have been shown to increase visitor retention and loyalty and user satisfaction, especially for users with slow internet connections and those on mobile devices.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Web performance also leads to less data travelling across the web, which in turn lowers a website's power consumption and environmental impact.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Some aspects which can affect the speed of page load include browser/server cache, image optimization, and encryption (for example SSL), which can affect the time it takes for pages to render.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] The performance of the web page can be improved through techniques such as multi-layered cache, light weight design of presentation layer components and asynchronous communication with server side components.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] In the first decade or so of the web's existence, web performance improvement was focused mainly on optimizing website code and pushing hardware limitations.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] According to the 2002 book *Web Performance Tuning* by Patrick Killelea, some of the early techniques used were to use simple servlets or CGI, increase server memory, and look for packet loss and retransmission.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Although these principles now comprise much of the optimized foundation of internet applications, they differ from current optimization theory in that there was much less of an attempt to improve the browser display speed.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Steve Souders coined the term "web performance optimization" in 2004.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] At that time Souders made several predictions regarding the impact that WPO as an "emerging industry" would bring to the web, such as websites being fast by default, consolidation, web standards for performance, environmental impacts of optimization, and speed as a differentiator.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] One major point that Souders made in 2007 is that at least 80% of the time that it takes to download and view a website is controlled by the front-end structure.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] This lag time can be decreased through awareness of typical browser behavior, as well as of how HTTP works.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Web performance optimization improves user experience (UX) when visiting a website and therefore is highly desired by web designers and web developers.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] They employ several techniques that streamline web optimization tasks to decrease web page load times.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] This process is known as front end optimization (FEO) or content optimization.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] In addition to the techniques listed below, the use of a content delivery network—a group of proxy servers spread across various locations around the globe—is an efficient delivery system that chooses a server for a specific user based on network proximity.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Typically the server with the quickest response time is selected.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Web browsers open separate Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) connections for each Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) request submitted when downloading a web page.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] These requests total the number of page elements required for download.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] However, a browser is limited to opening only a certain number of simultaneous connections to a single host.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] To prevent bottlenecks, the number of individual page elements are reduced using resource consolidation whereby smaller files (such as images) are bundled together into one file.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] This reduces HTTP requests and the number of "round trips" required to load a web page.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Web pages are constructed from code files such JavaScript and Hypertext Markup Language (HTML).
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] As web pages grow in complexity, so do their code files and subsequently their load times.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] File compression can reduce code files by about 40 percent, thereby improving site responsiveness.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Web Caching Optimization reduces server load, bandwidth usage and latency.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] CDNs use dedicated web caching software to store copies of documents passing through their system.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Many website platforms, such as SiteGround, IONOS, Wix, and Hostinger, rely on global CDNs and caching technologies to deliver faster page loads across different geographical regions.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Subsequent requests from the cache may be fulfilled should certain conditions apply.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Web caches are located on either the client side (forward position) or web-server side (reverse position) of a CDN.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Web browsers are also able to store content for re-use through the HTTP cache or web cache.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Requests web browsers make are typically routed to the HTTP cache to validate if a cached response may be used to fulfill a request.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] If such a match is made, the response is fulfilled from the cache.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] This can be helpful for reducing network latency and costs associated with data-transfer.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] The HTTP cache is configured using request and response headers.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Code minification distinguishes discrepancies between codes written by web developers and how network elements interpret code.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Minification removes comments and extra spaces as well as crunch variable names in order to minimize code, decreasing files sizes by as much as 60%.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] In addition to caching and compression, lossy compression techniques (similar to those used with audio files) remove non-essential header information and lower original image quality on many high resolution images.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] These changes, such as pixel complexity or color gradations, are transparent to the end-user and do not noticeably affect perception of the image.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Another technique is the replacement of raster graphics with resolution-independent vector graphics.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Vector substitution is best suited for simple geometric images.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Lazy loading of images and video reduces initial page load time, initial page weight, and system resource usage, all of which have positive impacts on website performance.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] It is used to defer initialization of an object right until the point at which it is needed.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] The browser loads the images in a page or post when they are needed such as when the user scrolls down the page and not all images at once, which is the default behavior, and naturally, takes more time.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Since web browsers use multiple TCP connections for parallel user requests, congestion and browser monopolization of network resources may occur.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Because HTTP/1 requests come with associated overhead, web performance is impacted by limited bandwidth and increased usage.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Instead of a website's hosting server, CDNs are used in tandem with HTTP/2 in order to better serve the end-user with web resources such as images, JavaScript files and Cascading Style Sheet (CSS) files since a CDN's location is usually in closer proximity to the end-user.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] In recent years, several metrics have been introduced that help developers measure various aspects of the performance of their websites.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Modules to measure metrics such as TTFB, FCP, LCP, FP etc are provided with major frontend JavaScript libraries such as React, NuxtJS and Vue.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] Google publishes a library, the core-web-vitals library that allows for easy measurement of these metrics in frontend applications.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] In addition to this, Google also provides the Lighthouse, a Chrome dev-tools component and PageSpeed Insight a site that allows developers to measure and compare the performance of their website with Google's recommended minimums and maximums.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/web-performance] In addition to this, tools such as the Network Monitor by Mozilla Firefox help provide insight into network-level slowdowns that might occur during transmission of data.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Website monitoring companies provide organizations the ability to consistently monitor a website or server function and observe how it responds.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] The monitoring is often conducted from several locations around the world to a specific website, or server, to detect issues related to general Internet latency, and network hop issues, and to prevent false positives caused by local or inter-connect problems.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Monitoring companies generally report on these tests in a variety of reports, charts, and graphs.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] When an error is detected monitoring services send out alerts via email, SMS, phone, SNMP trap, a pager that may include diagnostic information, such as a network traceroute, code capture of a web page's HTML file, a screenshot of a webpage, and even a video of a website failing.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] These diagnostics allow network administrators and webmasters to correct issues faster.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Monitoring gathers extensive data on website performance, such as load times, server response times, and page element performance that is often analyzed and used to further optimize website performance.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Monitoring is essential to ensure that a website is available to users, downtime is minimized, and performance can be optimized.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Some platforms, like Webflow, Wix, and Duda, handle hosting and monitoring internally, providing visibility into uptime and performance without requiring third-party monitoring tools.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Users that rely on a website or an application for work or pleasure will get frustrated or even stop using the application if it is not reliably available.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Monitoring can cover many things that an application needs to function, like network connectivity, Domain Name System records, database connectivity, bandwidth, and computer resources like free RAM, CPU load, disk space, events, etc.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Commonly measured metrics are response time and availability (or uptime), but consistency and reliability metrics are gaining popularity.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Measuring a website's availability and reliability under various amounts of traffic is often referred to as load testing.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Website monitoring also helps benchmark the website against the performance of a competitor to help determine how well a site is performing.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Website speed is also used as a metric for search engine rankings.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Website monitoring can be used to hold web hosting providers accountable for their service-level agreements.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Most web hosts offer a 99.9% uptime guarantee and when uptime is less than that, individuals can be refunded for the excessive downtime.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Not all hosts will refund individuals for excessive downtime so one must become familiar with the terms of service of their host.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Most paid website monitoring services will also offer security features such as virus and malware scanning which is of growing importance as websites become more complicated and integral to the business.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Website monitoring can be done from both *inside* and *outside* of a corporate firewall.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Traditional network management solutions focus on *inside the firewall monitoring*, whereas *external performance monitoring* will test and monitor performance issues across the Internet backbone and in some cases all the way to the end-user.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Third-party website performance monitoring solutions can monitor internal (behind the firewall), external (customer-facing), or cloud-based Web applications.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Inside the firewall, monitoring is done by special hardware appliances which can help you determine if your internal applications’ sluggish performance is caused by: the design of applications, internal infrastructure, internal applications or connections to any public Internet.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] External performance monitoring is also known as end-user monitoring or end-to-end performance monitoring.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Real user monitoring measures the performance and availability experienced by actual users, diagnoses individual incidents, and tracks the impact of a change.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] A website monitoring service can check other internet protocols besides HTTP pages and HTTPS such as FTP, SMTP, POP3, ActiveSync, IMAP, DNS, SSH, Telnet, SSL, TCP, PING, UDP, SOAP, Domain Name Expiry, SSL Certificate Expiry and a range of ports.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Monitoring frequency occurs at intervals of once every 4-hours to every 15-seconds.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Typically, most website monitoring services test a server, or application, between a once-per-hour per once-per-minute.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Advanced monitoring services capture browser interactions with websites using macro recorders, or browser add-ons such as Selenium or iMacros.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] These services test a website by running a web browser through a typical website transaction (such as a shopping cart) or a custom scenario, in order to check for user experience issues, performance problems, and availability errors.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Browser-driven monitoring services detect not only network and server issues, but also webpage object issues (such as slow loading JavaScript, or third-party hosted page elements).
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Implementation of time performance monitoring for the Apache HTTP Server is the mod_arm4 module.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Users of website monitoring (typically network administrators, webmasters, web operations personnel) may monitor a single page of a website, but can also monitor a complete business process (often referred to as multi-step transactions).
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Website monitoring services usually have a number of servers around the globe – South America, Africa, North America, Europe, Africa, Asia, Australia and other locations.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] By having multiple servers in different geographic locations, a monitoring service can determine if a web server is available across continents over the Internet.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Some vendors claim that the more locations the better picture of your website availability while others say that three globally distributed stations are sufficient and more stations do not give more information.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Some monitoring services use multi-region consensus, where an alert is only triggered when a failure is confirmed from multiple independent probe locations simultaneously, rather than from a single location.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] As the information brought by website monitoring services is in most cases urgent and may be of crucial importance, various notification methods, often known as "alerts" are used: e-mail, IM, regular and cell phones, SMS, fax, pagers, Skype, RSS Feed, SNMP trap, URL notifications, etc.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] The Website monitoring market is very competitive.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] There are 150+ active service providers and more than 100 are documented to have gone out of business.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] Most of the providers offer a free plan with low-frequency monitoring.
[src:synthetic-monitoring/website-monitoring] In recent years Synthetic Monitoring services have become widely available commercially, providing another vehicle to monitor the performance of specific web properties at a granular level.
